The paper deals with multi-task learning in the context of visual perception tasks, specifically segmentation, depth, and motion estimation. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also proposes a novel multi-stream multi-task network architecture and a new loss function, which involves optimization and machine learning techniques, indicating that it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper's focus on autonomous driving and visual perception tasks suggests that it could also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The paper's use of feature representations from preceding frames in a video sequence suggests that it could also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper's experimental results on various datasets suggest that it could also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
